  "prompt": "Why don't we pray and offer pooja for Lord Brahma?",
  "response": "There are several reasons why Lord Brahma is not commonly worshipped compared to other Hindu deities like Vishnu and Shiva:\n\n1. Mythology reasons:\n- According to a legend, Brahma was cursed by Lord Shiva for lying\n- Another story suggests he was cursed by his own creation, Saraswati\n- These curses reportedly reduced his importance in Hindu worship\n\n2. Philosophical interpretations:\n- Brahma represents creation, which is already complete\n- His role as creator is considered temporary and less significant compared to preservation (Vishnu) and transformation (Shiva)\n\n3. Symbolic significance:\n- Creation is a one-time process\n- Preservation and destruction are continuous processes\n- Hence, Vishnu and Shiva receive more devotional attention\n\n4. Limited temples:\n- Very few temples are dedicated exclusively to Brahma\n- The most famous Brahma temple is in Pushkar, Rajasthan\n\n5. Scriptural emphasis:\n- Most Hindu scriptures focus more on Vishnu and Shiva\n- Brahma's narratives are comparatively limited\n\nThese reasons collectively explain why Lord Brahma receives less worship and devotional attention in Hindu traditions.",
